Patch from MiniMyth2 project

Developed-by: Piotr Oniszczuk <piotr.oniszczuk@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Piotr Oniszczuk <piotr.oniszczuk@gmail.com>



From f79517942f48ff70e8d346d41d25afe4f2ba1dc1 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jernej Skrabec <jernej.skrabec@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 07:54:02 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 17/27] iommu: sun50i: support DRAM above the 32-bit boundary

On boards with 4 GiB of DRAM, the top gigabyte lies above the 32-bit
physical address boundary (DRAM starts at 0x40000000), so the driver
refused to map those pages and large allocations for VE/DE randomly
failed with "attempt to map address beyond 4GB".

The IOMMU emits 32-bit bus addresses and the interconnect wraps them
modulo 4 GiB, mapping the otherwise meaningless bus range
[0, DRAM base) onto the top gigabyte of DRAM.  Any DRAM page is
therefore uniquely addressable through the low 32 bits of its physical
address.  The vendor sunxi-iommu driver relies on the same wraparound.

Accept physical addresses up to 4 GiB + DRAM base in map() (the PTE
naturally truncates to the low 32 bits) and add the 4 GiB offset back
when decoding a PTE whose page address lies below the DRAM base.

Page table allocations are already constrained to DMA32 and are not
affected.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_019m4MPFATiJUdhA7nbwr9pk
---
 drivers/iommu/sun50i-iommu.c | 27 +++++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 23 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/iommu/sun50i-iommu.c b/drivers/iommu/sun50i-iommu.c
index d4696da42..0a932394e 100644
--- a/drivers/iommu/sun50i-iommu.c
+++ b/drivers/iommu/sun50i-iommu.c
@@ -254,9 +254,23 @@ enum sun50i_iommu_aci {
 #define SUN50I_PTE_ACI_MASK		GENMASK(7, 4)
 #define SUN50I_PTE_PAGE_VALID		BIT(1)
 
+/*
+ * The IOMMU can only input and output 32-bit addresses, but DRAM starts
+ * above address 0, so on boards with 4 GiB the top of DRAM lies above
+ * the 32-bit boundary.  The interconnect wraps bus addresses modulo
+ * 4 GiB, mapping the otherwise meaningless (MMIO) bus range
+ * [0, DRAM base) onto that top part, so any DRAM page is uniquely
+ * addressable through its physical address's low 32 bits.  The vendor
+ * driver relies on the same wraparound.
+ */
 static phys_addr_t sun50i_pte_get_page_address(u32 pte)
 {
-	return (phys_addr_t)pte & SUN50I_PTE_PAGE_ADDRESS_MASK;
+	phys_addr_t page = (phys_addr_t)pte & SUN50I_PTE_PAGE_ADDRESS_MASK;
+
+	if (page < PHYS_OFFSET)
+		page += SZ_4G;
+
+	return page;
 }
 
 static enum sun50i_iommu_aci sun50i_get_pte_aci(u32 pte)
@@ -602,11 +616,16 @@ static int sun50i_iommu_map(struct iommu_domain *domain, unsigned long iova,
 	u32 *page_table, *pte_addr;
 	int ret = 0;
 
-	/* the IOMMU can only handle 32-bit addresses, both input and output */
-	if ((uint64_t)paddr >> 32) {
+	/*
+	 * Pages above the 4 GiB boundary are reached through the
+	 * interconnect's address wraparound; only addresses beyond
+	 * DRAM can't be represented.  sun50i_mk_pte() truncates the
+	 * physical address to its low 32 bits.
+	 */
+	if ((uint64_t)paddr >= PHYS_OFFSET + SZ_4G) {
 		ret = -EINVAL;
 		dev_warn_once(iommu->dev,
-			      "attempt to map address beyond 4GB\n");
+			      "attempt to map address beyond 4GB DRAM\n");
 		goto out;
 	}
 
